Starting dLocal
---------------

*Sebasti=C3=A1n Kanovich and Pedro Arnt, welcome to Stratechery.*

*Sebasti=C3=A1n Kanovic:* Ben, it=E2=80=99s great to be here. Thanks very m=
uch for having us.

*Pedro Arnt:* Thank you so much.

*Sebasti=C3=A1n, let=E2=80=99s start with you. Tell me about your backgroun=
d. Where did you grow up? How=E2=80=99d you get started with technology?*

*SK:* Born in Uruguay, been living in Israel for the last eight years. Tech=
nology was absolutely by chance. I started this journey when I was 21 and t=
his is what I=E2=80=99ve been doing for the last 12 years. To me, it all ca=
me from a problem that we found, which was payments weren=E2=80=99t working=
 in Uruguay, where I come from, and that=E2=80=99s how I got into technolog=
y. But it was by chance, I=E2=80=99m an economist by training.

*What was the specific moment where you realized this is a problem to be so=
lved and you think that you could do it?*

*SK:* I love the NBA, as we=E2=80=99ve discussed in the past, and I couldn=
=E2=80=99t buy my League Pass and I couldn=E2=80=99t buy anything online, a=
nd I was borrowing a credit card from people around the family and all of m=
y friends were doing the same, and that wasn=E2=80=99t the way things worke=
d in the US and Europe. I wasn=E2=80=99t the only one going through that, s=
o there was no =E2=80=9CWow=E2=80=9D moment because payment is never =E2=80=
=9CWow=E2=80=9D. But there was, =E2=80=9COkay, there=E2=80=99s something br=
oken here=E2=80=9D.

*How did you get started? You mentioned you were an economist. How did you =
get a team together, take this on? What=E2=80=99s the origin story here?*

*SK:* I met two of my partners who are older than I am, and they were assem=
bling the initial team, and I decided to join. I was much less conscious th=
an most on what I was getting into. The idea was, =E2=80=9COkay, we have th=
is small company/kiosk that we are solving a problem for one customer, let=
=E2=80=99s see if we can make it a little bit bigger=E2=80=9D. I wasn=E2=80=
=99t getting into the startup world, I wasn=E2=80=99t getting into the VC w=
orld, then coming from Uruguay, and twelve years ago, that wasn=E2=80=99t t=
hat obvious that those opportunities were out there, so I joined. I was wor=
king at Santander Bank. This seemed to be a more exciting thing to do, I di=
dn=E2=80=99t have to wear a suit, and I went for it.

*You mentioned there was a single kiosk. What was the first problem that dL=
ocal was solving? And how did you go from there to serving large multinatio=
nals as you do today?*

*SK:* The first product we had was in Brazil with a thing called Boleto ( h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boleto ) , which was a cash method, it=E2=80=
=99s now replaced by Pix ( https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pix_(payment_syste=
m) ). The previous iteration of that, people used to pay in Brazil with a c=
ash slip, the solution we found was users were now able to, when they went =
into the checkout with the cashier, they were now able to issue one of thes=
e Boletos and then they would go to a bank or a kiosk and literally pay in =
cash. We thought we had solved every problem in life. We said, =E2=80=9COka=
y, this is the solution for everything=E2=80=9D.

Then we realized that it wasn=E2=80=99t only Brazil, it wasn=E2=80=99t only=
 about Boleto, it was all across LatAm, it was all across Africa, it was al=
l across Asia and people have not one way of paying, they have thousands of=
 way of paying. But the initial idea of what we did, which is users want to=
 pay with local payment methods, it=E2=80=99s exactly the same today as it =
was 12 years ago.

*So if you start out with Boletos and the local grocery store and kiosk, or=
 whatever it might be, I=E2=80=99m still trying to understand, what=E2=80=
=99s the path of getting from there to working with say a Microsoft or an A=
irbnb?*

*SK:* You start small. What we found was that as we started going, we alway=
s dreamt of having these US customers. Facebook was a dream customer for us=
, or Google was the thing and what we realized when we first went there was=
 that they told us, =E2=80=9CYes, we have a problem.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s =
not that they didn=E2=80=99t know about this problem, but for a few years a=
t the beginning they would tell us, =E2=80=9CLook, it=E2=80=99s interesting=
, but international for us means Europe, so I=E2=80=99m not going to go and=
 have any solution around Latin America or Brazil.=E2=80=9D

Over time what happened was two things. One is that emerging markets became=
 more relevant for global companies, so everyone would have a strategy at F=
acebook and Google and Apple and Netflix thinking of where to find growth, =
and at the same time we stopped being one payment method and we went on to =
aggregate over 600 payment methods, so the value proposition started to com=
pound. We are not just solving Boletos in Brazil, we are solving every paym=
ent method in Brazil, but under the same API, we=E2=80=99re going to do Mex=
ico and we=E2=80=99re going to do South Africa, and we=E2=80=99re going to =
do Nigeria, and we=E2=80=99re going to do Indonesia and suddenly that conve=
rsation becomes much, much easier. Two things happened, the underlying tren=
ds and we building a much more comprehensive product.

*What was your first big customer in the US that wanted to use you to go ab=
road?*

*SK:* GoDaddy.com. I still remember those visits, it was incredibly painful=
 because back in the day we tried to be B2C before being B2B, so we had a p=
repaid card with a brand of ours, and GoDaddy told us, =E2=80=9CLook, it=E2=
=80=99s beautiful what you do, but no one cares about your brand. Give us t=
he payment methods, so just go from the payment method to the cashier.=E2=
=80=9D We were a little bit offended at first because, again, we=E2=80=99re=
 trying to build a brand. But they were right, we were better suited to be =
an infrastructure player, and GoDaddy essentially helped us build the produ=
ct that then all the others bought.

One API
-------

*So today the core value proposition of dLocal is your primary customers ar=
e mostly American companies, large companies, they want to do business in e=
merging markets. They go to you, you have one API, and you=E2=80=99ll take =
care of all the details. Is that the proposition?*

*SK:* Yes. Small caveat, Ben, it=E2=80=99s not only American companies, it=
=E2=80=99s any global companies. We do a lot with Chinese companies, so the=
 likes of Shein and Alibaba going international, a lot of European companie=
s, and obviously the big American ones. Essentially, anyone who wants to do=
 business in emerging markets today is speaking with us or using our servic=
es.

We are behind the scenes a pure infrastructure play, we don=E2=80=99t have =
any agenda whatsoever around owning end customers. But we want to build inf=
rastructure. Part of what we did, we started from a bank, which is what I w=
as describing before, a user buying from a company. But then Uber came and =
said, =E2=80=9CI need to pay out to my drivers, can we also do that?=E2=80=
=9D And then Shein came and say, =E2=80=9COkay, now I need a marketplace be=
cause I need to onboard thousands of servers.=E2=80=9D So the evolution of =
the dLocal has been, =E2=80=9CHow do we cater to these global merchants and=
 how do we solve more problems for them in emerging markets=E2=80=9D?

