the percentage. We care about, =E2=80=9CAre we going to get more dollars, f=
ree cash flow dollars that are going to flow through our platform?=E2=80=9D=
, and if the answer is =E2=80=9CYes=E2=80=9D, we should definitely go for i=
t.

The Future
----------

*Just out of curiosity, thinking about myself personally, the worst anecdat=
a given the scale you=E2=80=99re operating at, but when I came to Taiwan tw=
enty years ago, everything was cash, and you had to always have cash on han=
d. Now you have an aspect where credit cards are very widely dispersed and =
again, because it came along late, it=E2=80=99s quite advanced. You can use=
 your phone for basically everything these days.*

*To what extent do you see similar trends around the world? Will credit car=
ds take over in the end? Or is there a bit where, obviously we saw China go=
 straight to more wallet solutions, I=E2=80=99m just curious on a broader t=
rend. The US and Europe, we=E2=80=99re all familiar with that. But what tre=
nds do you see worldwide as far as payments? Are credit cards going to be a=
 thing, or is it going to stay a mishmash, or is there something else that=
=E2=80=99s going to win the day?*

*PA:* Yeah, sure. It=E2=80=99s super interesting. One of the things that=E2=
=80=99s happening is in many emerging markets you=E2=80=99re seeing some of=
 the most interesting innovation around non-credit card rails, and that=E2=
=80=99s because if you look at things like Pix in Brazil, or UPI in India (=
 https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unified_Payments_Interface ) , or these digi=
tal wallets, they actually offer a better experience, and the rails are typ=
ically cheaper than what Visa and Master have built globally.

That=E2=80=99s another reason why we=E2=80=99re so bullish on the long-term=
 opportunity here is that we actually think, and we=E2=80=99re seeing it in=
 many of these markets, you see the emergence of payment mechanisms that st=
art decreasing the reliance on cash. Now mind you, cash for most of our mar=
kets is still more than 50% of transactions, but they=E2=80=99re not migrat=
ing to credit cards as the Taiwan example you gave us, they=E2=80=99re migr=
ating elsewhere. Real-time payments, central bank clearing houses, digital =
wallets with massive market share, like the Chinese example. I think, reall=
y, that=E2=80=99s what we=E2=80=99re seeing across the global south.

*Do you still have kiosks?*

*SK:* Yes, in many places, Ben. One thing we learned very early on, because=
 obviously we don=E2=80=99t like cash, we prefer any =E2=80=94 we are payme=
nt geeks, we like UPI, Pix much better than a cash kiosk, but you don=E2=80=
=99t educate the users, we are not in that business. We are in the business=
 of offering whatever payment method users want to pay with. So if it=E2=80=
=99s cash in Egypt, which we don=E2=80=99t love, that=E2=80=99s what we got=
 to offer, otherwise, we=E2=80=99re leaving 50% of the population.

Pedro was referring to conversion rate as, =E2=80=9COkay, how many more bip=
s I get on a credit card transaction, or what higher percentage rate?=E2=80=
=9D, for us, conversion rate means also, =E2=80=9COkay, you=E2=80=99re goin=
g to get access to 50% of the population that wasn=E2=80=99t even able to p=
ay you because they went to do the checkout and they couldn=E2=80=99t find =
a payment method=E2=80=9D. So it needs to be really inclusive, independent =
of what we think of the payment method itself.

Over the long run, cash should go away, credit cards are there to stay, but=
 there=E2=80=99s also credit cards which are enabling installments, so that=
=E2=80=99s a local flavor. So it=E2=80=99s still credit cards, but they beh=
ave slightly different. Debit cards are becoming more and more relevant. If=
 anything, we=E2=80=99re seeing payment methods becoming more fragmented, t=
he world of payment methods, it=E2=80=99s less consolidated than it was bef=
ore.

*You mentioned that you=E2=80=99re starting to get more into the remittance=
s business, which turns the flow of cash in the opposite direction.*

*SK:* Absolutely, yes.

*And so, how does that work? You mentioned you don=E2=80=99t want to go dir=
ect-to-consumer, you=E2=80=99re a B2B brand, so how do you =E2=80=94 remitt=
ances is the most, it=E2=80=99s like C2C in some respects.*

*SK:* Yes, but there are nine or ten key remittance players that process ov=
er 80% of the market. The same way we serve Facebook, Google, Netflix, Appl=
e, Amazon and Microsoft, we want to serve those same nine or ten on the rem=
ittance space. We are not going to be competing with them, that=E2=80=99s a=
 huge advantage. We=E2=80=99re going to be serving them and using the rails=
 that we built for others for that use case.

That required us to step up our compliance function and monitoring function=
 to make sure we understand who our counterparts were from a remittance sta=
ndpoint, we stayed away from that space forever. But when you look at what=
=E2=80=99s going on in that space and where the GDP of the Internet is goin=
g from, or going and coming from, remittances, it=E2=80=99s definitely a pl=
ace where we decided that we want to have way more exposure and we have all=
 the competitive advantages. We already have the flows, we already have the=
 infrastructure, the licensing. We in many cases have the opposite flows, a=
s Pedro was saying before, so it=E2=80=99s a no-brainer for us to be able t=
o compete in that space and have a better solution.

*Is this a situation where ideally you leave money in a market so you=E2=80=
=99re not even doing currency transfers at all? So to the extent you can ba=
lance ins and outs in each individual market, then you=E2=80=99re just movi=
ng some numbers on a ledger instead of actually doing conversions.*

*PA:* That=E2=80=99s exactly it, where it=E2=80=99s permitted by regulation=
, which is in most of these markets. If you think about it, the remittance =
providers are looking for two things, speed and cost, and that kind of just=
 moving money on a ledger, but where there=E2=80=99s no actual money transi=
tion, gives us an incredibly competitive offering in terms of those two thi=
ngs, which is speed and price.

*The reason to have the talk this week, you are announcing =E2=80=94 we=E2=
=80=99re having this interview before earnings, it is embargoed until after=
 then, so I don=E2=80=99t know what happened in your earnings, that=E2=80=
=99s why I=E2=80=99m not asking you about it yet, but I believe you=E2=80=
=99re announcing that you are no longer doing the co-CEO thing, that was a =
temporary thing. Sebasti=C3=A1n, where are you going?*

*SK:* Going nowhere, going to the board. Ben, I love this company too much,=
 I=E2=80=99m going to still be around. I=E2=80=99m going to be leading wher=
e we=E2=80=99re establishing a commercial and M&A committee that I=E2=80=99=
m going to be leading. But it=E2=80=99s time for me to step down as CEO, it=
=E2=80=99s been a huge ride and an incredible one but as a public company a=
nd looking ahead, I think Pedro is in much better position to do it. I=E2=
=80=99m going to be supporting the company, but from one step behind, which=
 is a place I feel a little bit more comfortable with as well.

*Pedro, did you know this was going to happen when you came onboard last fa=
ll?*

*PA:* Obviously, like we=E2=80=99ve always said, Seba is the one who came l=
ooking for me. I think we=E2=80=99ve run this with a really interesting blu=
eprint of how to make a very difficult transition not only from a CEO to a =
CEO, but from a founding CEO to the guy that=E2=80=99s brought in, which is=
 always quite difficult.

I think the transition period, the fact that I=E2=80=99ve been able to spen=
d a lot of time with Seba, seeing how he managed this, how he built this, h=
e=E2=80=99s also been incredibly constructive about biting his lip when he=
=E2=80=99s seeing I=E2=80=99m doing something in a different way, but allow=
ing me to gradually step into the position. So yes, this has always been th=
e plan, this has always been the way we thought it through. We didn=E2=80=
=99t put any specific dates to our plan, because we wanted to see organical=
ly how it played out and at least in terms of the actual transition, I thin=
k both internally and externally, this is a phenomenal way to do it. Now it=
=E2=80=99s up to me to deliver the way he=E2=80=99s delivered over the last=
 seven years.

*There were reports late last summer ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/artic=
les/2023-08-14/latin-american-payments-provider-dlocal-said-to-explore-sale=
 ) , Sebasti=C3=A1n, that you were potentially looking for buyers and this =
came on the heels of these challenges over the last 16 months, is a way to =
put it. Was this a situation where you stepped back and decided, actually, =
=E2=80=9CThis company should keep going down this road, we just need new le=
adership=E2=80=9D? What was your thought process through there?*

*SK:* Ben, the reports that we were looking to get bought, we were never lo=
oking for buyers, those were the reports and obviously they weren=E2=80=99t=
 real, otherwise we=E2=80=99re not here.

Ben, I started this company when I was 22, I=E2=80=99m now 33, close to 34,=
 one kid-and-a-half at home. I felt that starting in Uruguay, getting to th=
e public markets, three years in the public markets, delivering on what I b=
elieve to be an incredible story and the business is in a very unique posit=
ion. There=E2=80=99s a lot of moats, there=E2=80=99s a lot of things that a=
re very unique to what we built, and at the same time, building a public co=
mpany is a different skill. I never thought we would get Pedro, it was impo=
ssible to get Pedro, Pedro is a superstar of this market of ours.

You spoke about the market reaction when Pedro joined, I had the same react=
ion when I first thought of the possibility of getting Pedro to join. I wou=
ldn=E2=80=99t be leaving this company to anyone, I=E2=80=99m not leaving th=
e company, but I wouldn=E2=80=99t be leaving the leadership to anyone. As P=
edro was saying, I just care too much about this, I sweat every single cent=
imeter of growth that we=E2=80=99ve had. I really feel that we have the rig=
ht team, the right person in charge and I=E2=80=99m also very excited to se=
e what we build next.

Sometimes it=E2=80=99s like a kid that grew up and I want to see where it c=
ontinues, and I want to be hopefully helping in as much as I can. Kids some=
times don=E2=80=99t want to listen too much to the old guy and I=E2=80=99m =
not an old guy, but I also need to understand that. But again, it=E2=80=99s=
 a very happy day for me today, that I can tell you.

*What=E2=80=99s next, Pedro? What are those plans? What are the things that=
 =E2=80=94 again, I get the core proposition of dLocal. There=E2=80=99s a l=
ot of details I don=E2=80=99t get, which is kind of the point, you take car=
e of all the details for us dummies sitting in developed worlds. But where =
do you see this going and what do you see driving growth continuing going f=
orward?*

*PA:* What=E2=80=99s great about where we=E2=80=99re at right now is, what =
you=E2=80=99ve just referred to as the core proposition gives us significan=
tly leeway for growth. Just by offering our existing merchant base more geo=
graphies, and then also growing their share of wallet in the geographies wh=
ere we=E2=80=99re already processing for them.

Remember that in many cases they don=E2=80=99t have a single provider, they=
 may have two or typically what happens is that they=E2=80=99re still proce=
ssing international credit cards, which is more expensive and less efficien=
t for them, and as they grow comfortable with our value prop and what we=E2=
=80=99re offering, more of that flow goes to us and less of it is done thro=
ugh an international credit card transaction.

So just from adding share of wallet and new geographies to the existing mer=
chant base, there=E2=80=99s significant tailwinds. Overlay that with new me=
rchants that we offer the same core set of products we have today, and that=
=E2=80=99s another significant growth driver for us. When we think of what=
=E2=80=99s happening with the digital revolution and all the new digital se=
rvices that are coming up, and that eventually emerging market consumers wi=
ll want to access and will have to pay for.

Snd then the third piece is we continue to innovate on products. Always ver=
y close to our core knowledge, which is payments, but there=E2=80=99s whole=
 verticals we haven=E2=80=99t attacked yet. Can we help banks be faster and=
 cheaper with the way that they deliver small scale international money tra=
nsmission? Absolutely. SWIFT is still a legacy system that=E2=80=99s still =
expensive and still relatively slow. What can we do in terms of helping glo=
bal treasuries with invoicing and accounts receivables and accounts payable=
s? So we do have a pipeline of new products that will eventually hit market=
, and we sell those things to existing merchants and new merchants. When yo=
u think about it, the way we=E2=80=99ve phrased all this is we will grow by=
 growing share of wallet of our existing merchants by adding new merchants =
and by overlaying new products.

*How do you balance that with shoring up the foundations? Again, just treme=
ndous growth for a decade with tremendous complexity, that=E2=80=99s the bi=
t I keep coming back to, the exact value proposition, that core proposition=
 is so compelling, but it also is really hard and hard to get right. How do=
 you strike the balance there?*

*PA:* I think great companies are the ones that are able to avoid the trade=
-offs that not-great companies come up against. What I=E2=80=99ve been tell=
ing folks here is, =E2=80=9CLook, we=E2=80=99re a great company, you guys a=
re great managers of this company, and we need to be able to run and chew g=
um at the same time=E2=80=9D. That means we need to be able to capture all =
this growth that we have ahead of us, and at the same time, we need to buil=
d solid foundations so that we can manage all of that incremental volume on=
 behalf of our merchants without hiccups, and I think it=E2=80=99s fair tha=
t you ask the question, because we don=E2=80=99t like easy, easy is boring.=
 But I don=E2=80=99t think it=E2=80=99s necessarily a trade-off where eithe=
r you grow or you build scalable internal systems and processes, the good c=
ompanies like ours will figure out the way to do both.

*If we talk again in three years or five years, what are the markers? What =
am I looking at to say that you pulled it off, it=E2=80=99s even greater th=
an we expected?*

*PA:* All the internal stuff is the stuff we shouldn=E2=80=99t talk about. =
At the end of the day, that=E2=80=99s just building the foundations so that=
 we can have more TPV, which means that our merchants are increasingly choo=
sing us.

So the markers are, =E2=80=9CHave you sustained your TPV growth over a mult=
i-year period?=E2=80=9D, which when you start compounding makes for an enor=
mous growth story. =E2=80=9CAre you still delivering best in class margins?=
=E2=80=9D, which means that not only do you have a high growth business, bu=
t you have a high growth business with a really attractive financial model =
which is very high in margin and delivering operational leverage, and spitt=
ing out cash the way we do our cash conversion from net income is above 100=
%. So when you think about it, we=E2=80=99re doing two things at once, we h=
ave a really interesting purpose, which is making sure that billions of eme=
rging market consumers are able to access the digital revolution, that won=
=E2=80=99t happen without companies like ours, and at the same time, we can=
 generate significant value to our shareholders because we combine growth w=
ith margin and cash generation. All the internal stuff is just to allow tha=
t to happen.

*How important is it going to be to capture not just multinationals but loc=
al companies? You=E2=80=99ve had big growth in things like car services, wh=
ich are multinationals to an extent, but it=E2=80=99s more internal circula=
tion to a company. Do you think you=E2=80=99ll always be from developed mar=
kets to emerging markets, or are some of these markets going to become more=
 self-contained over time?*

*PA:* We=E2=80=99re really good about understanding where we add value. Do =
we add that much value to a large Mexican retailer who only has a business =
in Mexico? Probably not. The concept of a single API, the concept of intere=
sting FX products and helping you navigate FX complexity resonates a lot le=
ss with that merchant. So we typically don=E2=80=99t really target a mercha=
nt unless he operates in two, three, or more markets and the addressable ma=
rket there is just gigantic as globalization occurs. When that Mexican reta=
iler says, =E2=80=9CYou know what, I now want to add Costa Rica and Peru, b=
ecause we=E2=80=99re going international,=E2=80=9D that=E2=80=99s where we =
become relevant to them. The guys that are just very large in one market, s=
ure they=E2=80=99ll knock on our door and we might show them what we can do=
 for them, but that=E2=80=99s not who we=E2=80=99re focusing on.

*Have you ever thought, ever wondered, Sebasti=C3=A1n as you look back, may=
be we should just stuck with Latin America, that would=E2=80=99ve made it e=
asier? Or does this have to be a global product?*

*SK:* Absolutely not! Africa and Asia today represent over 20% of our busin=
ess. They=E2=80=99re going to be way, way, way more than that. We started i=
n Latin America because that=E2=80=99s where we are from, but when you see =
the challenges that someone has to process a payment in Nigeria, it=E2=80=
=99s exactly the same from what we saw in Brazil ten years ago. You have cr=
azy valuations and it looks complex and Brazil today, it=E2=80=99s commodit=
ized, if you will and when we first process a payment in Brazil, it was imp=
ossible to do.

We get excited about that, we are very excited about Bangladesh and Pakista=
n, which are two extremely complex markets from a payment standpoint but th=
e future of our company, it=E2=80=99s to abstract as many complexities as p=
ossible. Staying only in LatAm would=E2=80=99ve been a very, very bad mista=
ke for us and I=E2=80=99m extremely excited and happy that we did it. It wa=
sn=E2=80=99t easy, but we should continue to invest there.

*Well, I=E2=80=99ll have to ask you the same question, now that you=E2=80=
=99re Pedro=E2=80=99s boss, or grandfather, or whatever the analogy was. Wh=
at makes you feel satisfied in three to five years when you look at what=E2=
=80=99s happened? What do you want to see occur?*

*SK:* (laughing) Ben, partner, not boss, not grandfather, partner. Absolute=
ly. Look, I think a good thing about the local strategy that it=E2=80=99s e=
asy. We spoke about it with Pedro, it=E2=80=99s not rocket science from a s=
trategic standpoint, everything that Pedro described, I would sign right be=
low it. The execution of it is extremely complex, I think we know what we n=
eed to build, we know where we need to build it, it=E2=80=99s going to be e=
xtremely complex. You need to continue to have the right culture, continue =
to stay very humble, continue to stay very hungry, and build a company that=
 can be transformational.

One of the challenges we=E2=80=99ve always had is that we are bad communica=
tors and I hope that as we get our story out there more and more, people wi=
ll be able to recognize how unique what we are building is. Merchants do re=
cognize it, and that=E2=80=99s why we get the trust of those. But I think i=
n the next three to five years you=E2=80=99ll see us becoming a company tha=
t=E2=80=99s much bigger, but most importantly having a much bigger impact, =
because there=E2=80=99s plenty of space with it.

*Well, it=E2=80=99s certainly been quite a story, quite a run. Congratulati=
ons, Sebasti=C3=A1n on a decade. Congratulations on surviving the last coup=
le of years in particular and Pedro, it=E2=80=99ll be interesting to watch =
and see how things go.*

*PA:* Thank you.

*SK:* I really appreciate it.

